  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide standardized frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute money laundering\n- Extradition agreements\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Establishing common standards for:\n- Customer due diligence\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance\n\n4. Supranational Enforcement\n- International organizations monitoring compliance\n- Sanctions for non-cooperative jurisdictions\n- Pressure to implement robust AML regulations\n\n5. Jurisdictional Cooperation\n- Cross-border investigation mechanisms\n- Coordinated legal actions\n- Sharing of intelligence and evidence\n\n6. Financial Sector Regulations\n- International banking standards\n- Transparency requirements\n- Transaction tracking protocols\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive global approach to preventing and detecting money laundering activities.",
